description:
raft.ts:57-88 — RaftMessage has 12 optional fields shared across 4 message types. A RequestVote message has candidateId but NOT entries/leaderCommit. All are optional because one flat interface serves all types.

This allows constructing invalid messages (RequestVote with entries field) and accessing missing fields without TypeScript warning.

Convert to discriminated union:
```typescript
type RaftMessage =
  | { type: 'RequestVote'; from: string; to: string; term: number;
      candidateId: string; lastLogIndex: number; lastLogTerm: number }
  | { type: 'RequestVoteResponse'; from: string; to: string; term: number;
      voteGranted: boolean }
  | { type: 'AppendEntries'; from: string; to: string; term: number;
      leaderId: string; prevLogIndex: number; prevLogTerm: number;
      entries: LogEntry[]; leaderCommit: number }
  | { type: 'AppendEntriesResponse'; from: string; to: string; term: number;
      success: boolean; matchIndex?: number };
```

This makes handleMessage at :560 type-narrow correctly in each switch case.

map-reduce.ts:20 — MRStep.data is Record<string, unknown>. The UI at DistributedModule.tsx:2222-2389 must cast: (data.chunks as string[]), (data.pairs as string[]), (data.reduced as Record<string, number>), etc. These casts are unsafe — a typo in the key name would compile but crash at runtime.

Replace with:
```typescript
type MRStep =
  | { phase: 'split'; tick: number; description: string;
      chunks: string[]; chunkCount: number; totalWords: number }
  | { phase: 'map'; tick: number; description: string;
      chunkIndex: number; input: string; pairs: string[] }
  | { phase: 'shuffle'; tick: number; description: string;
      groups: Record<string, number[]>; uniqueKeys: number }
  | { phase: 'reduce'; tick: number; description: string;
      reduced: Record<string, number> }
  | { phase: 'output'; tick: number; description: string;
      counts: Record<string, number>; topWords: string[] };
```

This eliminates all `as` casts in MapReduceCanvas.

crdt.ts:497 returns `unknown` from getValue(). crdt.ts:512 returns Record<string, unknown> from getAllValues(). The CRDT type IS known at construction time (crdtType field) but not propagated through the type system.

Option A — overloaded getValue:
```typescript
getValue(replicaId: string): CRDTValue;
// where CRDTValue = number | string | null | string[]
```

Option B — generic simulation:
```typescript
class CRDTSimulation<T extends CRDTType> {
  getValue(replicaId: string): CRDTValueFor<T>;
}
```

Option A is simpler. The UI already handles all types via formatValue() — this just adds type safety to the intermediate layer.

DistributedModule.tsx:552 — GenericEvent is a meaningless name. It's used as the unified type for the bottom panel event log. Fields: { tick, type, description }.

Rename to SimulationLogEntry and add optional fields that engines can populate:
```typescript
interface SimulationLogEntry {
  tick: number;
  type: string; // TODO: union of all event types
  description: string;
  sourceNodeId?: string; // from RaftEvent.nodeId, GossipEvent.from, etc.
  severity?: 'info' | 'warning' | 'error'; // for color-coding
}
```

This enables the event log to show source node and severity without the unsafe RaftEvent cast.

Adding a new simulation requires touching ~7 locations in 2 files with zero TypeScript guidance. The DistributedSim union type can be extended but nothing forces the developer to add a canvas, controls, or properties for the new sim.

Define:
```typescript
interface DistributedSimulation<T extends DistributedSim> {
  id: T;
  meta: SimDef;
  createEngine: () => SimulationEngine;
  Canvas: React.ComponentType<CanvasProps>;
  Controls: React.ComponentType<ControlProps>;
  Properties: React.ComponentType;
}

const SIMULATION_REGISTRY: { [K in DistributedSim]: DistributedSimulation<K> } = {
  raft: { ... },
  'consistent-hashing': { ... },
  // TypeScript ERROR if any sim is missing!
};
```

This makes adding a new simulation a compile-checked operation.
